What is the equation of the following graph in terms of the cosine function?

\(y=\)[[input:ans1]] [[validation:ans1]]

generalfeedback.text: Recall that the general cosine function is written as \(y = a \cos b(x-c)+d\). First notice that the graph is of a wave form which oscillates between \(-4\) and \(2\). Therefore the amplitude is \((4 + 2)/2 = 3\), hence \(a = 3\). Now notice that the principal axis is the line \(y = -1\) so \(d =-1\). Also, we can see that there is one period from \(0^\circ\) to \(360^\circ\) hence \(b =1\). However, we can see that the graph has been shifted horizontally from the plot of the function \(y = \cos x\). In fact, it has been shifted right by \(90^\circ\), therefore \(c = 90\).Hence the equation of the graph is \[ y={@ta1@} \]
